FTC Sues to Block Activision Deal (Again)
-----------------------------------------

From the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/articles/ftc-plans-to-se=
ek-a-restraining-order-to-stop-microsoft-from-closing-activision-deal-305e1=
30b ) :

The Federal Trade Commission on Monday asked a federal court to prevent Mic=
rosoft from closing its $75 billion acquisition of Activision Blizzard whil=
e the agency carries out a separate process to block the deal. The FTC soug=
ht an injunction in San Francisco federal court, citing recent media report=
s that said Microsoft was considering closing the deal despite legal opposi=
tion in the U.S. and U.K. A judge would need to agree to issue the injuncti=
on, likely after a hearing at which the FTC would present evidence for why =
the deal is illegal=E2=80=A6

Microsoft announced its plans to buy Activision in January 2022 and valued =
the deal at $69 billion after adjusting for the videogame publisher=E2=80=
=99s net cash. The companies had planned to close the transaction next mont=
h. In December, the FTC sued to block the deal, saying it would be illegal =
because it would give Microsoft the ability to control how consumers beyond=
 users of its own Xbox consoles and subscription services access Activision=
=E2=80=99s games. The company could raise prices for people who don=E2=80=
=99t use Microsoft=E2=80=99s hardware to access the games, or even cut off =
access entirely, the FTC argued.

The FTC filed that suit in its in-house court and at the time didn=E2=80=99=
t seek an emergency order to stop the deal because the closing date was mor=
e than seven months away. A trial in the FTC=E2=80=99s in-house court is sc=
heduled for early August, but it could take months after the trial for the =
administrative law judge to issue a decision. For now, the two cases will p=
roceed in parallel. The FTC said in its complaint that an injunction is cri=
tical because allowing the acquisition to close before the August hearing w=
ould enable Microsoft to start altering Activision=E2=80=99s operations and=
 business plans, access the company=E2=80=99s sensitive information, elimin=
ate key Activision personnel, change its game development efforts and enter=
 into new contractual relationships on behalf of Activision.

If a judge denies the injunction, it would be a blow to the FTC=E2=80=99s a=
ssertion that the Microsoft-Activision deal is illegal. The commission coul=
d continue its separate, in-house lawsuit, but the FTC more often drops its=
 opposition to a deal if a judge denies an injunction. That is what happene=
d with Meta Platforms=E2=80=99 acquisition of virtual-reality company Withi=
n Unlimited. After a judge in San Jose, Calif., ruled against the FTC=E2=80=
=99s request for an injunction, the agency abandoned the in-house court pro=
ceeding it had launched against Meta.

There are a few interesting things going on here:

* First, the FTC=E2=80=99s argument is largely in line with its initial law=
suit filed in its in-house court; I made the case against that argument whe=
n it was filed in Consoles and Competition ( https://stratechery.com/2022/c=
onsoles-and-competition/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF=
0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVye=
S5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJlbnQiOnsidXJpIjpbImh0dHBzOi8vc3RyYXRlY2hlcnkuY29t=
LzIwMjIvY29uc29sZXMtYW5kLWNvbXBldGl0aW9uLyJdfSwiZXhwIjoxNjg5MjU1OTk5LCJpYXQ=
iOjE2ODY2NjM5OTksImlzcyI6Imh0dHBzOi8vc3RyYXRlY2hlcnkucGFzc3BvcnQub25saW5lL2=
9hdXRoIiwic2NvcGUiOiJmZWVkOnJlYWQgYXJ0aWNsZTpyZWFkIGFzc2V0OnJlYWQgY2F0ZWdvc=
nk6cmVhZCIsInN1YiI6IlJzZXVZRThqZ0hlUHBXSmYxZkFiNEMiLCJ1c2UiOiJhY2Nlc3MifQ.j=
9LNke-v2LRk0wRcJa8vI0iKJNP5o8x-iHPgugqlJXKb3ebbQCqvRdi5fUGKHBYlZWqT-luO0nrc=
FPKpmh1onnTA4rsLsQTI1Rc_bqsZbSPQMxD8CURksT1ZyC103WXqirj5JGPN3r46wZy13fkwm3d=
8dphtQAbus8mHrYKg0CsH2kRWKHrKCa9D7sHMDIUouj1Zr-X7KxLVtDZyvp1B5uihkgkPweOdLa=
rSKpAgybkPQfesQgeRr73oMPui1GZgB9VEfxKa3N25-bFX5QTBsMRrp8dt-2kvz6sbRstk1YDY8=
ykHszzvuKd4EQ0540j_IRKTCB6dzFzplPDwXAndyg ).
* Second, while the saying goes that =E2=80=9Conce is chance, twice is a co=
incidence, and three times is a trend=E2=80=9D, it does seem notable that t=
his is the second time the FTC has quickly filed a case against a big tech =
acquisition in its internal court, and then filed a case in federal court s=
everal months later. A cynical interpretation might be that all acquisition=
s are going to receive an FTC lawsuit immediately in front of their in-hous=
e court, and that evidence collected for that initial lawsuit will later be=
 leveraged for a lawsuit in federal court; that said, I=E2=80=99m not a law=
yer, so maybe I=E2=80=99m reading too much into this.
* Third, the Microsoft Activision acquisition announcement was on January 1=
8, 2022, and the deadline for closing the deal was 18 months hence, i.e. Ju=
ly 18, 2023. I too have heard that Microsoft is leaning towards simply clos=
ing the deal, confident it will win the case in the U.S. and that it can ma=
nage the U.K. rejection by either winning on appeal or by somehow cutting t=
he U.K. off.

Global Companies vs. Regional Regulators
----------------------------------------

With regards to that last point, from the same Wall Street Journal article:

Doing the deal without the U.K. might be an option, some lawyers say. Micro=
soft could cut off the U.K. from accessing Activision games via the cloud, =
said David Hoppe, a mergers-and-acquisitions, tech and media attorney with =
Gamma Law in San Francisco. The CMA in March said it had narrowed the focus=
 of its probe into the proposed acquisition to the cloud-gaming market, rem=
oving previous concerns that the deal could lessen competition in the estab=
lished and much larger console-gaming market.

I don=E2=80=99t have a point of view on this; my (weakly held and relativel=
y uninformed) assumption was that Microsoft would have to exit the U.K. mar=
ket completely if it didn=E2=80=99t want to abide by the CMA=E2=80=99s deci=
sion, which obviously wasn=E2=80=99t going to happen given that most of Mic=
rosoft=E2=80=99s business (1) has nothing to do with Xbox and (2) is what a=
ctually makes the company money. However, the calculus is a lot different i=
f the only question is removing Activision in the cloud, or Xbox Game Pass =
generally, or even Xbox as a whole; in that case the importance of Xbox Gam=
e Pass to Microsoft in terms of justifying continued investment in the Xbox=
 game business very likely outweighs having access to the U.K. market for t=
hose specific businesses.

Microsoft=E2=80=99s decision =E2=80=94 and what the U.K. does about it =E2=
=80=94 obviously also has a bearing on other future big tech acquisitions a=
nd the relative power global regulators have on stopping them. If every acq=
uisition risks the entire business than regulators with markets that are U.=
K.-sized have effective veto power on every acquisition; however, if Micros=
oft successfully maintains its core business in the U.K. and simply sacrifi=
ces Xbox Game Pass or Xbox generally then that will mean two things:

* First, the only regulators with the power to stop an acquisition will be =
those in the very largest markets, particularly the U.S. and E.U. (and, dep=
ending on the product, China).
* Second, smaller regulators like the CMA will be heavily incentivized to n=
ot rock the boat, since the primary harm from ruling against an acquisition=
 will be in depriving their own citizens of the product in question.

I can definitely understand the squeamishness of folks that feel like a big=
 tech company is simply flipping its nose up at a government regulator; at =
the same time, it=E2=80=99s fair to ask if relatively small market regulato=
rs should have effective jurisdiction over an entire global business: why s=
hould a U.K. regulator get to decide if U.S. or E.U. citizens get access to=
 Activision titles on Xbox Game Pass?

To be clear, and to reiterate the point above, Microsoft has always had the=
 option of exiting the U.K. market completely; the bet in this case is that=
 the U.K. wouldn=E2=80=99t be willing to kick out Microsoft=E2=80=99s non-g=
aming business given that so many U.K. citizens and businesses (and probabl=
y the CMA itself) depend on their products, which gets to the broader chall=
enge of tech and antitrust: the problem from a regulatory perspective isn=
=E2=80=99t that people are forced to use tech products, it=E2=80=99s that t=
hey want to (although, to be fair, Microsoft=E2=80=99s file format lock-in,=
 to the extent it still exists, is closer to the =E2=80=9Cforced to=E2=80=
=9D side of the equation).

