There honestly wasn=E2=80=99t much else in the post, but I did find this tw=
eet from the event interesting:

( https://twitter.com/stephentotilo/status/1667987717660221441?ref_src=3Dtw=
src%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1667987717660221441%7Ctwgr%5E7e2=
96cbbc476396cdc057de1edbfd94ba72861bb%7Ctwcon%5Es1_&ref_url=3Dhttp%3A%2F%2F=
chrome-headless.local%3A9222%2Fatomic )

First off, I wonder if the $1 billion reference is actually about the subsc=
ription revenue in the excerpt above; secondly, a doubling of gaming revenu=
e since the Xbox 360 era =E2=80=94 which started in 2005 =E2=80=94 isn=E2=
=80=99t that impressive when you realize that Microsoft=E2=80=99s overall r=
evenue has increased 4x in the same time period (I measured from 2007, as t=
hat is the equivalent time in the Xbox 360=E2=80=99s lifecycle as we are in=
 the Xbox Series X/S lifecycle).

What is particularly weird about this last point is that Microsoft=E2=80=99=
s 2007 annual report stated ( https://www.microsoft.com/investor/reports/ar=
07/staticversion/10k_dl_dow.html ) :

Xbox and PC game revenue increased $650 million or 19% as a result of incre=
ased Xbox 360 platform sales, partially offset by decreased sales of the fi=
rst generation Xbox console and related accessories and video games.

=E2=80=9CIncreased $650 million or 19%=E2=80=9D implies just over $4 billio=
n in revenue; meanwhile, from last year=E2=80=99s annual report ( https://w=
ww.microsoft.com/investor/reports/ar22/index.html ) :

Gaming revenue increased $860 million or 6% on a strong prior year comparab=
le that benefited from Xbox Series X|S launches and stay-at-home scenarios,=
 driven by growth in Xbox hardware and Xbox content and services. Xbox hard=
ware revenue increased 16% due to continued demand for Xbox Series X|S. Xbo=
x content and services revenue increased 3% driven by growth in Xbox Game P=
ass subscriptions and first- party content, offset in part by a decline in =
third-party content.

=E2=80=9CIncreased $860 million or 6%=E2=80=9D implies around $15 billion i=
n revenue; for reference, =E2=80=9Cgaming revenue=E2=80=9D is defined as:

Gaming, including Xbox hardware and Xbox content and services, comprising f=
irst- and third-party content (including games and in-game content), Xbox G=
ame Pass and other subscriptions, Xbox Cloud Gaming, third-party disc royal=
ties, advertising, and other cloud services.

I=E2=80=99m having a hard time squaring what appears to be a nearly 4x incr=
ease in revenue with Spencer=E2=80=99s reported statement that gaming reven=
ue has doubled; obviously I could be comparing the wrong years, or includin=
g the wrong things, or maybe the reporter misheard; after all, Spencer woul=
d presumably prefer to give a larger multiple instead of a smaller one.

The reason this matters is that it bears on the question of whether or not =
the Xbox business is worth it to Microsoft, particularly if they aren=E2=80=
=99t allowed to proceed with the Activision acquisition; of course we also =
need to understand how much this is costing the company, not just the top-l=
ine number, but I thought it worth pulling the actual numbers because 2x wo=
uld, in this case, actually be even more disappointing than I thought (and,=
 for the record, last year Playstation drove around $24 billion in revenue =
for Sony).

One other point that I mention on Sharp Tech (the one that will be released=
 shortly): Xbox Game Pass sure seems like a great match for the Vision Pro,=
 for both Microsoft and Apple. Apple gets a compelling gaming story, beyond=
 ported iOS games, and Microsoft gets both a compelling example of cloud ga=
ming=E2=80=99s value and an answer to PlayStation VR (no, these wouldn=E2=
=80=99t be VR games, but an immersive experience playing 2D games is very m=
uch aligned with how Apple is approaching entertainment). My assumption, th=
ough, is that Apple won=E2=80=99t allow Game Pass as a standalone app (a la=
 iOS), which would sort of answer the question as to whether or not the Vis=
ion Pro will ever be allowed to be a true Mac replacement.

